					The difference with organising #ThisKidCAN compared to other projects was that all 3 of our team who were involved in it were sooo enthusiastic and passionate which made the whole process seem a hell of a lot easier!
				</p>
				<p>
					At the time of organising #ThisKidCAN, part of my job role included managing a caseload of children with long-term physical disabilities some of which were very mild didn’t actually require regular input within school (we’re talking GMFCS I and II). This group of children were the initial catalyst which got us thinking about #ThisKidCAN. My colleague and I found ourselves getting fed up of hearing our own voices asking children to “make sure you complete your stretches” so we tried to think of alternative ways by which they could self-manage their own disability.
				</p>
				<p>
					Quite frankly, I don’t actually blame them for not stretching. Let’s face it, if you were a teenager, independent with everything and had no specific, reoccurring complaints of pain … would you sit and stretch just because some physio said so? … I guess a lot of physio’s already know the low compliance rates in completing exercise programmes in both children AND adult populations.
				</p>
				<p>
					So we thought about trying to improve their engagement differently by getting them participating in sports so they get to keep their physio’s happy while actually enjoying themselves with their mates!
				</p>
				<p>
					The other big reason for running #ThisKidCAN was to simply raise the profile of what adapted and inclusive sports/activities there were available locally. After the event, we hoped to create a leaflet for children’s parents so in the future when a parent says something like .. “my disabled child can’t join in” or “there’s nothing which my disabled child can do” or “everything is too far away” we will be able to simply give them a leaflet with a list of all the events going on.
				</p>
