				<p>
					Now back to fun literature, Shield and Sinnott (2016) completed a qualitative article on identifying the perceived barriers and facilitators to participation in physical activity for children with disability. #ThisKidCAN aimed to remove a proportion of these barriers. Parents reported difficulty finding suitable activities, felt fearful about their disabled child being included and struggled to find people with appropriate experience. #ThisKidCAN definitely removed this. Some of the other facilitators #ThisKidCAN also helped to improve were positive attitudes towards disability, financial assistance in payments and meeting similar children.
				</p>
				<p>
					I do agree with parents when they report having difficulty trying to find adapted and inclusive sports or activities. Even though the profile of disabled sports has improved ten fold over the past decade (thanks to the likes of Jamie Peacock and the other 2012 Paralympic superstars) we are actually still so far behind in ensuring appropriate adaptations are available for physically disabled people, particularly in the amateur setting. #ThisKidCAN was a baby step in tackling this problem … similarly to how switching your lights off is a baby step in saving the world from self-destruction ……. kind of?!
				</p>
				<p>
					The actual event organisation was a long and tedious task. For anyone hoping to organise something similar in their boroughs I’d love to give you some quick solution of how to do so but unfortunately persistence is key. Call, call and call again. We tried to get representation from all different activities from Yoga through to Martial Arts (there’s a list at the end with everyone who attended).
				</p>
